I have been using this for a few months now, here's my short review:

Sound: Clear voice, sharp and loud. Bass is quite soft.
ANC: Works realy good
Mic: The best so far. I have been using them for meetings. The voice are clear and I think they block noise as well.
Battery: this is the only problem that I have with the earbuds. it only lasted around 2h - 3h from a single use. if i have a back to back meetings, it's a bad news! 

Overall, for the affordable price it offers a great exprience! Really recommended. And I was surprised to know that it has wireless charging from this video. Now I can charge it with my samsung phone. LOL

Comment: These are an improvement over the 1st gen buds. https://www.youtube.com/post/UgkxK5mc3yw4xA7Mf2j6k6n1Uqv_KUgrKdeM Pros: The fit is fantastic. This is the biggest plus. They stay in my ears when running and become unnoticeable. They are tight but comfortable. The sound quality is about the same as the 1st gen buds. They pair more easily with my LG G8 ThinQ and immediately reconnect when removed from the case. The sound balance is excellent, good but not overpowering base and clean mid tones and highs.Cons: The noise cancellation is good but perhaps a little less effective than the Bose ANC on the 1st gen buds. Passthrough mode as not as good as the 1st gen buds making it a little more difficult to hear conversations when in passthrough.

Comment:
Okay I'm back a year later with my honest review. I bought the Redmi buds out of necessity, as I couldn't afford the Sony headphones I initially wanted. I decided to try them despite not being a fan of in-ear buds because they tend to slip out. I took a leap of faith and hoped these would be great.  

Right off the bat I wasn't blown away, the sound quality was just okay and I often found myself turning up the volume but it was never enough. The companion app offers features like noise canceling but to be honest it doesn't quite live up to expectations. During phone calls the receiver could barely hear me due to distortion and the audio sounding as though I was far away. The earbuds sync well but I've noticed a decrease in sound quality over time. At first I thought the flat sound was due to the battery being low, but it turns out the audio quality decreases after a few minutes of playback even with a full charge. The pause-on-tap feature can be buggy often triggered when I removed the earbuds or wear a hat. On the flip side, the case battery life is good requiring only 2-3 charges a month depending on how much you use them.

Overall I'd recommend sticking to classic plug-in earphones if you're looking for a place holder, I would not recommend these for long term use. All I can say is don't compromise on quality to save money - wait and invest in what you really want from the start because these kinda feel like a waste.

Comment:
Okay I'm back a year later with my honest review. I bought the Redmi buds out of necessity, as I couldn't afford the Sony headphones I initially wanted. I decided to try them despite not being a fan of in-ear buds because they tend to slip out. I took a leap of faith and hoped these would be great.  

Right off the bat I wasn't blown away, the sound quality was just okay and I often found myself turning up the volume but it was never enough. The companion app offers features like noise canceling but to be honest it doesn't quite live up to expectations. During phone calls the receiver could barely hear me due to distortion and the audio sounding as though I was far away. The earbuds sync well but I've noticed a decrease in sound quality over time. At first I thought the flat sound was due to the battery being low, but it turns out the audio quality decreases after a few minutes of playback even with a full charge. The pause-on-tap feature can be buggy often triggered when I removed the earbuds or wear a hat. On the flip side, the case battery life is good requiring only 2-3 charges a month depending on how much you use them.

Overall I'd recommend sticking to classic plug-in earphones if you're looking for a place holder, I would not recommend these for long term use. All I can say is don't compromise on quality to save money - wait and invest in what you really want from the start because these kinda feel like a waste of money.

Comment:
I bought them for 60‚Ç¨ trusting most of the reviews, which give very good reviews of these Redmi Buds 4 Pro.
They are very comfortable and I am very happy with the specifications but:

- Connected to my Xiaomi Redmi Note 8 pro phone, the sound that comes out of the headphones is very flat and the volume is not high, not even at maximum. The bass is very much in the background. Rockers/metalheads will miss these two shortcomings.
- The Xiaomi APP does not include an equalizer. Just an option to enhance bass that is barely noticeable (and that does not solve the problem of low volume).
- All this is solved by installing and playing your mobile music using wimAmp or another APP that equalizes the sound. They sound brutal through WimAmp.

The problem comes when we connect them to other devices such as the TV or PC. The equalization of third-party APPs installed on the mobile does not help us.
My Samsung SmartTv does not allow to equalize the sound of Bluetooth devices either... so you have to struggle with what the rickety Xiaomi APP offers you, which is basically NOTHING. That is, a flat sound with little bass.

GENTLEMEN OF XIAOMI, IS IT SO DIFFICULT TO IMPROVE YOUR APP WITH A DECENT EQUALIZER?

Comment:
STAY AWAY: boAt is a Total Scam and a Waste of Hard-Earned Money!

I am writing this to warn every single person out there: 
Do NOT fall for the marketing trap set by boAt. 

My experience with this company over the last four years has been nothing short of pathetic, and I‚Äôm done keeping quiet about this "scumbag" brand.

1) The "3-Month" Disposable Headphones
Four years ago, I fell for the hype and ordered a pair of their headphones(bassheads). They looked flashy in the ads, but the reality was a joke. Within 3 months, they were completely dead. One side stopped working, the plastic felt like it was made from recycled trash, and the "premium sound" they promise is just muddy, boosted bass to hide the terrible hardware. My 2000 rupees wasted instantly.

2) The Smartwatch That Software Killed
Thinking maybe it was a one-off issue, I made the mistake of buying the boAt Extend Smartwatch two years ago. It barely lasted 8 months.
Do you know how it died? A simple software update via their own app (boat wave) bricked the entire watch. It went from a working device to a useless piece of black glass overnight. When a company‚Äôs own "update" kills its product, you know their tech is absolute garbage. Again, 3000 rupees wasted instantly.

The Truth: Cheap Rebrands & Zero Value

Here is what boAt doesn't want you to know: They aren't "making" anything innovative. They are a white-labeling agency. They source the cheapest, "cheapsteak" electronics from local Chinese markets, slap a boAt logo on them, and sell them to Indian consumers at inflated prices under the guise of being a "homegrown" brand.

Quality: Laughable.
VFM (Value for Money): Zero. You are paying for their massive marketing budget, not the product.

After-Sales Service: Forget about it. If your product dies (and it will), their customer service will ghost you or give you the runaround until your warranty expires.

Final Verdict: Do yourself a favor and buy from a brand that actually invests in R&D and quality control instead of just "cool" advertisements. 

boAt is selling disposable e-waste, Don't be their next victim. Buy products that made of superior quality which lasts longer and help save  both your hard earned money and the environment.

This  earbuds are beautiful, but they‚Äôre not for everyone. The design is bulkier and doesn‚Äôt fit well in smaller ears. Additionally, the smooth texture and material cause them to slip, especially after prolonged use when natural earwax exacerbates the issue. This becomes problematic when the auto-pause feature is activated, as the sensor detects the earbud as removed even with slight head or mouth movements, or even talking.

The sound quality is excellent, with great volume and ambient effects. Noise cancellation works decently in terms of software, but due to the poor fit, it doesn‚Äôt perform well.

Pros

-Bluetooth connection is made very quick everytime.

-connect to multiple devices with ldac.

-sound quality is good for the price, but nothing impressive.¬†

-small case.¬†


Cons

-oval shape eartip nozzles. Hard to find replacement.¬†

-anc isn't as good as expected. Honestly, space a40 has better anc. I've tried with different eartip sizes and did the fit test in the app, but no improvement.

-doesn't produce feedback sounds when increasing or decreasing volume, but anc on or off it produces sound. Why inconsistent?


Overall I feel it's not as well made as anker products. I should have bought liberty 4 NC or pro.

I kind of regret buying it as it's not noticeably better than Space A40 which I already own. Space A40 is overall better as a whole package, including the quality of the app. I guess there is a difference in experience as tws manufacturer between Anker and Redmi. Anker product is more complete.


Score:

Space A40 8/10

Redmi buds 5 pro 5/10

Comment:
Bought these buds yesterday and so far my speculation about them:

1) very comfortable, they don't fall off which is very nice, the sound quality isnt that bad
2) battery life is poor, it is said they last 10hrs straight, but they only last 4-5hrs. In the first hour the battery will already have fallen down to 85%
3) constant and loud white noise. I know it's because of noise cancellation which you can turn off on the app, but as someone who needs noise cancellation it gets really annoying and distracting when listening to shit
4) the design is nice lol
5) redmi buds 3 pro had better noise cancellation. (these buds died after 2 years which is shitty tbh, so i hope these ones last longer)
6) the case battery is terrible. You will only be able to recharge the buds once, and the second time not even fully. Also, I found it weird that the case heats up while charging the buds?

     The battery being shit and the white noise being loud are my main problems with there earbuds, even tho my buds 3 pro only lasted 2 years, its battery n noise cancellation was so much better 
     Do I recommend? Only if they're on a huge sale. They're not worth the money they're being sold for.
